  <!-- BUYER'S GUIDE -->
  <section class="problem-section">
    <div class="problem-header">
      <span class="label-pill">Buyer's guide</span>
      <h2 class="h-lg">What to ask before buying <span class="accent">automated content publishing software.</span></h2>
      <p>Five questions that separate genuine auto-publishing tools from "auto-publishing" marketing.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="ba-grid">
      <div class="ba-col after" style="grid-column: 1 / -1;">
        <ul class="ba-list">
          <li><span class="ba-num">01</span><div><h4>Does it publish directly to your CMS, or does it export a file you paste in?</h4><p>This is the most important question. Some tools label themselves "auto-publishing" but generate a Google Doc, HTML file, or CSV that you still paste into your CMS manually. Ask for a live demo of the publishing step before subscribing.</p></div></li>
          <li><span class="ba-num">02</span><div><h4>Does formatting transfer correctly — headings, images, internal links, metadata?</h4><p>A broken H2 tag or missing featured image requires manual cleanup. Test the formatting accuracy on your specific CMS before committing to a monthly plan.</p></div></li>
          <li><span class="ba-num">03</span><div><h4>Does the tool generate content, or do you supply it?</h4><p>Publishing-only tools (CoSchedule, Letterdrop) require an existing content pipeline. Full-pipeline tools (theStacc, Journalist AI, Byword) generate and publish. Choose based on whether you already have writers or want full automation.</p></div></li>
          <li><span class="ba-num">04</span><div><h4>What happens if auto-publishing fails?</h4><p>Ask about failure handling. Does the tool notify you? Does it retry? Does it queue the article or skip it? Reliability matters more than feature count for a set-and-forget publishing workflow.</p></div></li>
          <li><span class="ba-num">05</span><div><h4>Is your CMS supported natively, or via Zapier?</h4><p>Native CMS integrations are more reliable than Zapier-based connections. Zapier adds latency, failure points, and a separate subscription cost. Confirm native support for your specific CMS before choosing a tool.</p></div></li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

